42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showPrevMessage?topicID=6.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showNextMessage?topicID=6.topic"> Next Topic >> </a> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95% cellpadding=5 cellspacing=1><tr><td valign=top bgcolor=32323c class=headings><font color=#ffffff>Author</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=32323c class=headings><font color=#ffffff>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=vanlaan>Vanlaan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(2/8/01 4:37:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://dntsvara.tripod.com/vanlaanpic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Vanlaan turned to head up the stairs and bed, when, for the second time that night, the door to the Inn crashed open.  A dwarf came storming in and began shouting at Vanlaan about a ring he had supposedly stolen.  Vanlaan stared at the dwarf, trying to remember if he had ever met him.  Dwarves pretty much all looked the same to him.  Even their women had hair on their faces.  The dwarf was so angry he was sputtering in Dwarven and Vanlaan really couldn't understand a word he was saying.  He really wished Aedare was here.  None of the patrons in the Inn were going to take Vanlaan's side.  He sighed.  This evening was not going as he had planned.<br>
<br>
He stepped towards the dwarf in an effort to calm him, and half the patrons in the Inn made threatening moves towards their weapons.  Okay, that wasn't going to work.  &quot;Friend dwarf,&quot; he said, &quot;please calm yourself so that we may discuss this matter rationally.&quot;  He continued racking his brain trying to remember any encounters with dwarves.  Suddenly, it came to him.  He and Aedare had met up with a young wood elf druid and this dwarf in the plague village.  For whatever reason that moves light-dwellers, they had given Vanlann and Aedare some armor and money at a time when they were desperately in need of assistance.  However, Vanlaan could not recall a ring.  He knew Aedare's honor would never allow her to stoop so low as to steal from anyone, even a paladin.  And what was Vanlaan going to do with a dwarven family crest?  The dwarf was still sputtering... he looked on the brink of apoplexy.  Vanlaan called softly to the Innkeep.  &quot;Could you perhaps serve the gentleman an ale?  Something to help him calm down?  I'm buying,&quot; and he threw a platinum on the bar.  The Innkeep, trying to avoid more mayhem in his bar, quickly drew an ale and walked it out to the dwarf.  Making no sudden moves, Vanlaan carefully returned to his seat.  &quot;Now then,&quot; he said, &quot;let's try for a more civilized tone, shall we.  I do remember the assistance that you and your druid companion offered Aedare and myself, for which we are most grateful, but I assure you, neither my companion or myself took any type of ring from you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Vanlaan sat and waited to see what the dwarf would do.  The atmosphere in the Inn was charged and it was obvious no one was tired any longer.  He sighed again.  He had really been looking forward to finding his bed after the day he had had.  He turned back to the dwarf.  Although obviously still angry, the dwarf did seem somewhat calmer.  &quot;Now then, tell me your name and let's see if we can figure out what's what.  By the way, where is your companion?&quot; <p><font face="Tahoma" color="#800000"><b>Vanlaan</b></font>
